+success_scenarios:
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a PR submitted on any Garura-managed project using a supported stack,
+      when quality-check runs in CI, then coverage delta and lint violations are surfaced
+      in the PR as reviewable findings within 3 minutes of CI run start, and quality-check
+      exits with a deterministic pass or fail in ≥ 95% of supported stack runs.
+    evidence: >
+      quality-check exit code is deterministic (0 = pass, non-0 = fail with findings)
+      in ≥ 95% of CI runs across supported stacks in a 30-day window. Coverage delta
+      appears in the PR review surface within 3 minutes of CI trigger. Measured by
+      CI run timestamps and PR comment timestamps.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a Garura-managed project with npm dependencies, when the security scanner
+      runs in CI, then a severity-tagged vulnerability list is available in the posture
+      dashboard within 5 minutes of the scan completing, showing only critical and high
+      severity items by default (medium/low filtered to a collapsed view).
+    evidence: >
+      Security posture dashboard for the project shows the vulnerability list within 5
+      minutes of scan completion. Dashboard default view contains only critical and high
+      items. Severity tagging covers all findings (critical/high/medium/low). Measured
+      by dashboard load time after scan completion.
+
+failure_scenarios:
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a coverage tool whose output format changes in an npm dependency update,
+      when quality-check runs with the new format, then the adapter fails to parse the
+      coverage output and quality-check silently exits 0 with no coverage data.
+    impact: >
+      Missing quality signal — coverage disappears from PRs without anyone noticing
+      on a solo-dev project. False confidence: green CI with no actual coverage data.
+      Solo-dev impact: no second engineer to notice the signal went silent.
+    mitigation: >
+      Stack-specific adapter tests verify coverage parsing on each CI run; format-change
+      detection emits a warning (not a silent pass) when coverage output is not parseable;
+      the quality-check step fails explicitly on parse error rather than silently succeeding.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a developer facing lint-noise fatigue from low-value lint rules, when they
+      disable a lint rule globally in the configuration, then the lint signal degrades
+      and subsequent PRs silently allow the suppressed issue type.
+    impact: >
+      Signal quality degrades; lint becomes theater rather than a real quality gate.
+      Suppressed rules are indistinguishable from rules that were never configured.
+    mitigation: >
+      Disable-comment requires a documented justification string; global rule disables
+      require a decision-manifest entry; CI flags any new global disable without
+      a justification comment as a lint policy violation.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a security scanner that produces 200 findings including low-severity CVEs
+      in transitive dependencies, when all findings are surfaced to the developer,
+      then the developer becomes overwhelmed and begins ignoring the security signal entirely.
+    impact: >
+      High-severity CVEs are lost in noise. Solo-dev lacks a security team to triage
+      separately — scanner noise overwhelm causes the developer to treat the signal
+      as background noise.
+    mitigation: >
+      Severity filtering + policy baseline: dashboard default view shows only critical
+      and high items; the policy threshold blocks PRs only on critical findings;
+      medium/low findings are available in an expandable view but do not block progress.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a coverage percentage that is high (e.g., 85%) but achievable through
+      covering only the happy path, when a developer ships a feature with shallow
+      assertions, then the coverage signal provides false confidence that the
+      implementation is well-tested.
+    impact: >
+      Defects slip through covered-but-empty test cases. The coverage signal is
+      misleading — a high percentage does not indicate meaningful scenario coverage.
+    mitigation: >
+      Coverage delta (not absolute percentage) is the primary surfaced metric per PR;
+      mutation testing is documented as a post-v1 planned enhancement for coverage
+      masking detection; developers are warned in the quality-check output that
+      high coverage does not guarantee scenario coverage.
+
