+success_scenarios:
+  - scenario: >
+      Given any Garura play with a valid intent.yaml and a locked epic, when evals-creator
+      runs as part of /create-play --build, then a step eval file exists for every play step
+      and a scenario eval file exists for every success and failure scenario in the intent,
+      with all evals passing on their canonical traces.
+    evidence: >
+      evals-creator exit code 0. Step eval file count equals play step count in intent.yaml.
+      Scenario eval count equals success_scenario count + failure_scenario count from the
+      epic. All evals pass when run against the canonical play trace captured at build time.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a defect filed against a Garura play using the report-issue workflow, when
+      fix-it completes the RCA-driven fix, then a regression test is linked to the defect
+      in STM and the fix does not reopen within the same milestone window in ≥ 95% of cases.
+    evidence: >
+      Regression test file exists in STM linked to the defect issue number. fix-it exit
+      code 0. Defect reopening rate < 5% measured across all defects closed by fix-it in
+      a 30-day window. Tracked via defect reopen events in the issue tracker.
+
+failure_scenarios:
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a play that has been rebuilt with a new intent.yaml version, when the associated
+      evals are not regenerated, then evals pass against the old intent but fail against
+      the new intent — tests are validating the wrong behavior silently.
+    impact: >
+      False positive passes — evals pass against stale scenarios. The defect surfaces
+      when a real user exercises the changed behavior, not in CI. Solo-dev impact:
+      no second reviewer to notice the eval-intent drift before the next release.
+    mitigation: >
+      evals-creator is invoked in /create-play --rebuild alongside the play recompilation;
+      a rebuilt play with unapplied eval updates is a blocking CI failure until evals
+      are regenerated.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a synthesized test whose scenario is ambiguous (multiple valid interpretations
+      of the then clause), when the test is run against an implementation that satisfies
+      one interpretation but violates another, then the test passes but the implementation
+      violates the intended scenario.
+    impact: >
+      Hollow test coverage — tests pass but the underlying intent is not verified.
+      Defects that violate the second interpretation are invisible to the test suite.
+    mitigation: >
+      Scenario structure discipline: scenarios.md Rule 1 (given/when/then format with
+      binary-testable then clauses) prevents ambiguous then clauses at authoring time;
+      scenario review gate before synthesis rejects ambiguous scenarios before tests
+      are synthesized.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a defect where fix-it proposes a fix that patches the symptom without
+      completing the 5-whys RCA, when the fix is merged, then the root cause recurs
+      at the next feature addition.
+    impact: >
+      Defect reopens; the same root cause is fixed multiple times independently —
+      methodology decays. Solo-dev impact: every recurrence costs full investigation
+      time with no team to distribute the load.
+    mitigation: >
+      fix-it enforces 5-whys RCA before proposing any fix; the RCA template is a
+      required output before fix-it enters the implementation step; a shallow RCA
+      (fewer than 3 why levels) is a blocking failure that requires the developer
+      to deepen the analysis before proceeding.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a fix validated by a regression test, when the same behavior is changed
+      by a later feature addition, then the regression test is not updated and the
+      defect resurfaces in the new context.
+    impact: >
+      Reopened defect with no updated regression test — fix-it loop breaks. The
+      original fix was correct but the regression test did not account for future
+      feature interactions.
+    mitigation: >
+      Regression test linked to defect in STM; check-drift includes regression test
+      staleness detection; any merge that touches the same code paths as a linked
+      regression test triggers a review flag.
+  - scenario: >
+      Given a repeated defect pattern occurring across multiple issues, when fix-it
+      treats each occurrence as an independent defect, then the same root cause is
+      fixed multiple times without recognizing the pattern.
+    impact: >
+      Methodology decay — the same root cause masquerades as different defects.
+      Pattern recognition is absent until a human reviewer notices the pattern.
+    mitigation: >
+      Defect-history check in fix-it: before beginning RCA, fix-it searches the
+      defect history for similar patterns and surfaces any matches; the pattern
+      library curation is tracked as a post-v1 Advanced enhancement.
+
