+    decision_type: "constraint-aggregation-pick"
+    tier: high
+    grounding_source:
+      kind: kb_path
+      ref: "/Users/kapilahuja/.claude/skills/derive-quality-profile-from-epics/SKILL.md"
+      excerpt: "if multiple epics have comparable targets, keep the strictest. Record the epic ID that sourced the target."
+    recommendation: >
+      Strictest-wins aggregation applied across all 9 epics. For performance_efficiency,
+      the strictest target across comparable dimensions is:
+        - Slash command invocation < 1s (EPIC-engineering-experience-cli-slash-commands-001)
+        - quality-check PR report < 3 minutes (EPIC-engineering-observability-quality-signals-001)
+        - Commit hook overhead < 200ms (EPIC-ai-governance-audit-attribution-001)
+        - Play invocation success >= 90% over rolling 30 days (EPIC-agentic-methodology-component-arch-001)
+        - evals-creator completes full play eval generation < 2 minutes (EPIC-work-intelligence-intent-driven-verification-001)
+      Where two epics named targets for the same dimension (e.g. audit bundle < 30s vs
+      security scanner < 5 min — distinct dimensions, no conflict), both are preserved
+      as separate targets sourced to their originating epic. No conflicting parallel targets
+      were found that required direct strictest-wins arbitration — all performance constraints
+      are for distinct operation types.
+    alternatives_considered:
+      - alt: "Union-preserving aggregation — all targets recorded independently without strictest-wins collapse"
+        why_not: >
+          Union preservation would leave the quality profile as a flat list of 9 epic-scoped
+          targets rather than a coherent product-level contract. Downstream build-arch consumers
+          cannot derive a single performance floor from a union list; they need a deterministic
+          product-level target per dimension.
+      - alt: "Context-scoped targets — different strictness per adopter segment (solo vs enterprise)"
+        why_not: >
+          Profile declares a single security_level=elevated and a single deployment model
+          (progressive). Context-scoping is a post-v1 complexity; v1 quality profile must
+          provide a uniform product floor. Segment-scoped quality profiles are a post-v1
+          enhancement.
+    agent_reasoning_summary: >
+      Each of the 9 epics defines performance constraints for its own operational scope
+      (command invocation, play execution, CI pipeline, eval generation). No two epics
+      name conflicting targets for the exact same operation. The strictest-wins rule is
+      applied as a safeguard but did not need to arbitrate any head-to-head conflict in
+      this epic set. All performance targets are preserved with their source epic cited.
